{{Update|date=June 2009}}

[[Djibouti]] had no proven reserves of [[oil]] or [[natural gas]], or refining capacity, Djibouti has no known reserves of [[coal]]. The country's  is supplied primarily by thermal plants (about 120 MW) and some imported hydro energy from [[Ethiopia]]. However, the supplemental supply of power from Ethiopia does not always satisfy Djibouti’s demand for power.<ref>DJIBOUTI
POWER AFRICA FACT SHEET [https://www.usaid.gov/powerafrica/djibouti]</ref> Based on 2013 data, Djibouti’s national electrification rate reached 50%, (14% in rural areas, 61% in urban areas).

==Electricity==
The peak annual demand in 2014 was about 90 MW but is expected that it will grow to about 300 MW by around 2020. Electricity supply services are provided through the vertically integrated utility Electricité de Djibouti (EDD). A small amount of additional energy is generated by a solar plant (300 kW capacity). Djibouti has wind and geothermal generation potential and is actively studying these options. 

==Petroleum==
All petroleum products are imported. In 2002, imports of refined petroleum products totaled {{convert|11410|oilbbl/d}}, with consumption placed at {{convert|11400|oilbbl/d}}. There were no natural gas imports for that year. The port in Djibouti's capital city is an important oil shipment and storage site.

